{"paperId": "28625648fae0a1ba915c5d2a19c312841afc1b1c", "title": "FakeFlow: Fake News Detection by Modeling the Flow of Affective Information", "abstract": "Fake news articles often stir the readers\u2019 attention by means of emotional appeals that arouse their feelings. Unlike in short news texts, authors of longer articles can exploit such affective factors to manipulate readers by adding exaggerations or fabricating events, in order to affect the readers\u2019 emotions. To capture this, we propose in this paper to model the flow of affective information in fake news articles using a neural architecture. The proposed model, FakeFlow, learns this flow by combining topic and affective information extracted from text. We evaluate the model\u2019s performance with several experiments on four real-world datasets. The results show that FakeFlow achieves superior results when compared against state-of-the-art methods, thus confirming the importance of capturing the flow of the affective information in news articles.", "venue": "Conference of the European Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics", "year": 2021, "citationCount": 52, "influentialCitationCount": 4, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://aclanthology.org/2021.eacl-main.56.pdf", "status": "HYBRID"}, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "The results show that FakeFlow achieves superior results when compared against state-of-the-art methods, thus confirming the importance of capturing the flow of the affective information in news articles."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [-0.6611698269844055, 0.8404844999313354, -0.6232162714004517, -0.3686974048614502, 0.2303144782781601, -0.08237432688474655, 1.1019868850708008, -0.07676565647125244, 0.055822063237428665, -0.20772956311702728, 0.471982479095459, 0.4761072099208832, 0.45303821563720703, -0.14645004272460938, -0.48022010922431946, 0.36866113543510437, -0.6367710828781128, 0.06949694454669952, -0.3091810941696167, -0.802327275276